      "id": "86a4310b6bd0359d",
      "text": "The exchange of goods is abstract because it is not only distinct from their use, but also separated in time. The act of exchange and the act of use are mutually exclusive. Sohn-Rethel explains: As long as goods are the subject of exchange negotiations, i.e. are on the market, they may not be put to use. During this time, they are subject to the fiction of complete physical immutability. The reason is that the act of exchange only changes the social status of the goods. In order to be able to carry out this social change properly and according to its own rules, the commodities must remain exempt from all physical changes. At the very least, it must be pretended to be so. This is why Sohn-Rethel can say that exchange is abstract even in the time it takes."
